tomatoes once they start turning red is it better to keep them on the vines or to pick them and let them rippen on the window sill great question i have different varietals of tomatoes too and i often wonder the same thing in the past i usually let the early season tomatoes ripen on the vine and at the end of the season when the weather starts cooling i'll pick those tomatoes and window ripen them also end of the season is great for fried green tomatoes if you've ever tried them it's a real treat and simple to make just slice them and dip them in egg and batter them with italian bread crumbs and pan fry delicious Japanese cuisine Cuisine of the Philippines Hamburger Cuisine of the Southern United States Fried chicken Cuisine of Denmark Breakfast Cuisine of Singapore Full English breakfast Potato chips Hot dog Soul food Cuisine of Brazil Deep frying Sandwich McDonald's Fish and chips Bread In-N-Out Burger Ketchup Barbecue D__ner kebab Cuisine of Greece Tofu German cuisine French toast Bengali cuisine Grilled cheese sandwich Cajun cuisine Butter Cha chaan teng Roe Mango Jewish cuisine Okra Cuisine of Malaysia Cuisine of Argentina Kebab Chili con carne French fries Cantonese cuisine Dosa 1957 World Series Fried Green Tomatoes at the Whistle Stop Cafe Pasta Shawarma French cuisine Dim sum Bagel Bacon Cookie Porridge Risotto Cuisine of Puerto Rico Pizza Hut Pancake Tobacco Paella Wiener schnitzel Gyros Maple syrup Naples Plantain Passover Vegetarian cuisine Korean cuisine Common bean Cuisine of South Africa Cooking New York Knicks Wok Oregano Gazpacho Salad Organic food Fruit Chicken Recipe Cuisine of Canada Fondue Avocado Sushi Carolina Panthers Futurama (TV series - season 4) Udon Cuisine of Vietnam Canadian Chinese cuisine Irish breakfast Historical roots of Catholic Eucharistic theology American Chinese cuisine Tilapia Coffee Dumpling Wine Philip J. Fry New Haven, Connecticut 